The respondent has been found guilty in Canada of the following offences:
12/8/99: Assault, for which he received a conditional discharge and 18 months probation;
25/9/00: Fail to comply with recognizance, for which he received 5 days jail (3 days PSC);
25/1/01: 2x mischief under $5,000, for which he was sentenced to 45 days internment (16 days PSC) and probation for 2 years.

[15]
The relevant provisions of IRPA states:
58. (1) The Immigration Division shall order the release of a permanent resident or a foreign national unless it is satisfied, taking into account prescribed factors, that
(a) they are a danger to the public;
(b) they are unlikely to appear for examination, an admissible hearing, removal from Canada, or at a proceeding that could lead to the making of a removal order by the Minister under subsection 44(2);
(c) the Minister is taking necessary steps to inquire into a reasonable suspicion that they are inadmissible on grounds of security or for violating human or international rights; gold
(d) the Minister is of the opinion that the identity of the foreign national has not been, but may be, established and they have not reasonably cooperated with the Minister by providing relevant information for the purpose of establishing their identity or the Minister is making reasonable efforts to establish their identity.
121(2) For the purposes of paragraph (1)(b), "criminal organization" means an organization that is believed on reasonable grounds to be or to have been engaged in activity that is part of a pattern of criminal activity planned and organized by a number of persons acting in concert in furtherance of the commission of an offense punishable under an Act of Parliament by way of indictment or in furtherance of the commission of an offense outside Canada that, if committed in Canada, would constitute such an offense.
58. (1) The section orders the release of the permanent resident or the foreigner, except upon proof, taking into account the regulatory criteria, of such of the following facts:
(a) the permanent resident or foreign national constitutes a danger to public safety;
(b) the permanent resident or foreign national is likely to evade control, investigation or removal, or the procedure that may lead to the Minister issuing a removal order under subsection 44(2);
(c) the Minister takes appropriate measures to investigate reasonable grounds to suspect that the permanent resident or foreign national is inadmissible for security reasons or for violations of human or international rights;
(d) in the event that the Minister considers that the identity of the foreign national has not been proven but can be proven, either the foreign national has not reasonably cooperated in providing the Minister with information useful for this purpose, or the latter is making valid efforts to establish the identity of the foreign national.
121(2) Criminal organization means an organization of which there are reasonable grounds to believe that it is engaged or has engaged in activities forming part of a plan of criminal activities organized by several persons acting in concert with a view to the commission of an offense under a federal law punishable by indictment or the commission, outside Canada, of an offense which, if committed in Canada, would constitute such an offence.
